Fill and boil your #kettle{}. Halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and
seeds. Slice into thin strips. Trim the @pak choi{1} then thinly slice widthways.

Pour the boiled water from the kettle into a large #saucepan{} with @salt{1/4%tsp}
for the noodles on high heat. When boiling, add the @egg noodle nest{2} to the
water and cook until tender, ~{4%minutes}. Once cooked, drain in a #colander{}.

> TIP: Run the noodles under cold water to stop them sticking together.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on high heat.
Once hot, add the @beef strips{240%g} to the pan and season with @salt{} and
@pepper{}. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat.
Fry until browned, ~{1-2%minutes}, continuously stirring.

> TIP: Don't crowd the pan or your beef strips will stew instead of fry. It's
> best to cook it in batches. Once each batch is browned, transfer it to rest on
> some kitchen paper.

> IMPORTANT: The beef is safe to eat when the outside is browned.

Wipe out the pan you used to cook the beef and return to medium-high heat with a
drizzle of @oil{drizzle}. When the pan is hot, add the sliced pepper and
stir-fry until tender, ~{4-5%minutes}. Once tender, add the bok choy and
stir-fry until tender, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Once the veggies are cooked, add the noodles and beef to the pan. Pour in the
@bulgogi sauce{150%g} and @soy sauce{25%ml} and stir-fry until piping hot,
~{1-2%minutes}.

> TIP: Add a splash of water if needed.

When everything is ready, share the bulgogi beef stir-fry between your bowls.
Enjoy!